For future production planning, this ownership model should be reviewed and updated if operational responsibility changes after the PoC.

## Current Business Driver

The business driver for this project is the planned exit from the True Value Chicago datacenter while preserving contractor desktop access for the Hexaware teams.

The PoC should help determine whether Azure Virtual Desktop is a viable replacement for the current VMware Horizon environment and whether the expected Azure operating cost is acceptable compared to the existing model and other migration options.

## Baseline

There is currently a VMware Horizon deployment hosted on premises in the True Value Chicago datacenter. It is primarily used by Hexaware consultants, with occasional use by a small number of other users.

The directive is to shut down the Chicago datacenter. As part of that effort, we are evaluating whether the existing VMware Horizon use case can be migrated to Azure Virtual Desktop.

## Proof of Concept Scope

As part of the Chicago datacenter exit, this project will build a disposable Proof of Concept for Azure Virtual Desktop.

The PoC is intended to determine whether Azure Virtual Desktop can meet the needs of the Hexaware contractor teams and to estimate the cost of running, managing, and maintaining the environment for budgetary planning.

The PoC should produce reusable Bicep modules, deployment patterns, documentation, and lessons learned that can inform a future production deployment. The PoC environment itself should not be treated as production.

## Technical Requirements and Constraints

### Disposable PoC

* The PoC environment is disposable.
* If the project moves forward to production, a new production environment will be deployed in a separate production subscription in the True Value Azure tenant.
* The PoC should still produce reusable Bicep modules, deployment patterns, documentation, and lessons learned for a future production deployment.

### Azure Landing Zone

* The Azure Landing Zone architecture has been deployed to True Value Azure using ALZ Accelerator code, with minor customization for the Do It Best / True Value naming scheme.
* The design is otherwise close to the Microsoft ALZ Accelerator example architecture.
* The AVD deployment will live in the Corp Landing Zone.
* The deployment will inherit the policies assigned to the basic example landing zone, with specific exceptions.
* DDoS protection and Microsoft Defender enforcement are not planned for the PoC unless that decision changes.

### Infrastructure as Code

* The environment should be deployed through Bicep and Azure DevOps pipelines.
* The PoC should support a smooth transition to a future production design by keeping infrastructure patterns reusable and understandable.
* Assume I am comfortable with infrastructure concepts but still building fluency with Bicep syntax, module design, deployment scopes, parameterization, and Azure Verified Module conventions.

### Azure Verified Modules

* Use Azure Verified Modules where practical.
* Do not force AVM usage where it makes the deployment harder to understand, harder to troubleshoot, or less appropriate for the PoC.

### FSLogix

* FSLogix will be used for user profile containers.
* Profiles will be stored in Azure Files storage.

### Active Directory Domain Services Join

* AVD session hosts will be joined to the `TV.local` Active Directory Domain Services domain.

## Non-Goals / Things Not to Optimize For

* Do not design this PoC as a permanent production environment.
* Do not prioritize manual portal configuration unless needed for testing or discovery.
* Do not assume personal desktops are required for all users.
* Do not assume pooled desktops will work for development users without validation.
* Do not recommend major architecture changes that conflict with the existing ALZ deployment unless there is a strong reason.
* Do not optimize only for lowest Azure cost if it compromises PoC validity.
* Do not assume the Chicago datacenter will remain available long-term.

## Environment Context

True Value has resources spread across several locations and cloud providers.

### Google Cloud Platform (GCP)

* Hosts the primary footprint of the True Value cloud infrastructure.
* Currently acts as the network hub for True Value cloud and site connectivity.
* Traffic from Azure to other True Value locations generally routes first to GCP, then to the appropriate datacenter, cloud provider, or other destination.

### Oracle Cloud

* Hosts some resources for the True Value Oracle Fusion deployment.

### AWS

* Hosts some True Value resources.
* The exact workloads and dependencies in AWS are currently unknown.

### Azure

* Since Do It Best acquired True Value, new cloud development has centered around Azure.
* True Value does not currently have a large footprint in its Azure tenant.
* True Value currently uses Microsoft 365 with Entra AD Connect configured.
* True Value Microsoft 365 is connected to Do It Best Microsoft 365 through MTO.
* Azure Lighthouse is not currently configured for the True Value Azure tenant.
* Most Do It Best Systems Engineering team members have been granted Global Administrator access in the True Value tenant so they can switch directories and manage the tenant.
* Subscriptions hosted in True Value Azure are billed through billing accounts and profiles that reside in the Do It Best directory and tenant.
* There is a dedicated True Value billing account with separate billing profiles and invoice sections for resources hosted in True Value Azure.

### Chicago Datacenter

* The Chicago datacenter is the primary True Value HQ datacenter.
* It hosts domain controllers, file shares, AIX, and other resources.
* As part of the Chicago datacenter exit, workloads are being evaluated for migration to cloud platforms, colocation facilities, or the Do It Best datacenter in Fort Wayne, Indiana.
* The True Value SD-WAN primarily treats the Chicago datacenter as the network communication hub for warehouses and cloud resources.
* True Value network redesign work is underway to reduce dependency on the Chicago datacenter.

### Cary, Illinois

* True Value owns a paint manufacturer in Cary, Illinois.
* This location hosts a large portion of the True Value disaster recovery environment.
* Do It Best has announced that this location is being sold to Sherwin-Williams.

