## Autoscale and Session Policy Requirements

The PoC should validate AVD autoscale and session behavior for each user group.

Current host pool settings should be verified in the repository before being documented or changed. Initial PoC settings should not be assumed to be final production policy.

### Policy Areas To Validate

For each host pool, confirm:

* Load balancing algorithm
* Maximum session limit
* Start VM on Connect behavior
* Idle session timeout
* Disconnected session timeout
* Logoff behavior
* Shutdown/deallocation behavior
* Business hours and off-hours behavior
* Weekend and holiday behavior
* Minimum available hosts
* Ramp-up and ramp-down behavior
* Whether autoscale is managed through AVD scaling plans, automation, pipeline configuration, or another mechanism

### User Group Considerations

| User Group / Host Pool              | Policy Consideration                                                                                                              |
| ----------------------------------- | --------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------- |
| Operations pooled                   | Should prioritize predictable 24x7 availability with cost-aware session controls                                                  |
| Development pooled                  | May require more generous idle/disconnect behavior because of development workflows                                               |
| Development personal                | Should not run unnecessarily when not in use; Start VM on Connect and shutdown behavior should be reviewed before assigning users |
| Operations personal, if added later | Should be exception-based and governed separately from pooled Operations desktops                                                 |

### Production Considerations

Before production deployment, confirm:

* Whether PoC session limits and timeout settings are acceptable for real users.
* Whether autoscale behavior meets support expectations.
* Whether shutdown behavior could interrupt long-running development work.
* Whether personal desktops need a separate lifecycle and cost-control process.
* Whether monitoring can prove autoscale and session policies are working as expected.

## Personal Desktop Lifecycle Requirements

Personal desktops have a different lifecycle than pooled session hosts and should be managed separately from core pooled AVD infrastructure.

For the PoC, personal desktop provisioning may be manual or pipeline-driven depending on what is implemented in the repository at the time of testing.

For production, the design should support a controlled lifecycle process for personal desktops.

### Lifecycle Capabilities To Define

The personal desktop lifecycle should eventually define how to:

* Request a personal desktop
* Approve or deny the request
* Select an appropriate VM size tier
* Provision the desktop
* Assign the desktop to a user
* Grant required access
* Apply required baseline configuration
* Resize the desktop
* Reassign the desktop
* Reclaim unused desktops
* Deprovision retired desktops
* Preserve or remove user data during deprovisioning
* Track ownership, cost, and business justification

### Size Tier Model

Personal desktop sizing should be controlled through human-readable Entra groups such as:

| Size Tier | Intended Use                            |
| --------- | --------------------------------------- |
| Small     | Lightweight personal desktop use        |
| Medium    | Standard personal desktop use           |
| Large     | Heavier development or tooling needs    |
| XL        | Exception-based high-resource workloads |

Automation should map each size-tier group to an approved Azure VM size.

The specific Azure VM size mapped to each tier should be verified in the repository or approved design documentation before being documented as final.

### Governance Requirements

Personal desktops should have stronger governance than pooled desktops because they can create persistent cost and support overhead.

Before assigning personal desktops in production, define:

* Who can request a personal desktop
* Who approves the request
* What business justification is required
* How long the assignment is valid
* How idle or unused desktops are detected
* How users are notified before reclamation
* Who pays for the desktop
* Whether chargeback or showback is required

